Description: This table catalogs the Amtrak train services within the Empire Corridor, highlighting the names of services, their routes, the dates services began and ended, along with notable operational changes or mergers. It provides a concise history of Amtrak's service evolution on these routes, enabling insights into the operational timeline, route adjustments, and service discontinuations or integrations into broader service offerings.

Header: Name, Route, Service began, Service ended, Notes
Entries:
Cayuga: Service between New York City and Schenectady from October 1984 to April 1987.
Central Park: Operated between New York City and Albany from April to October 1995, later merged into Empire Service.
DeWitt Clinton: Connected New York City and Albany from May 1974 to April 1981, replaced by Rip Van Winkle.
Electric City Express: Route from New York City to Schenectady starting in April 1981, replacing Salt City Express.
Empire Service: Two entries detailing routes from New York City to Buffalo (May 1971 to May 1974) and New York City to Niagara Falls (from October 1995 to present), with notes on the historical evolution and rebranding of services.
Empire State Express: Four entries detailing services between New York City and Buffalo/Detroit/Niagara Falls from May 1974, with notes on renaming and route changes.

This table delineates the timeline and operational specifics of Amtrak's Empire Corridor routes, encompassing both historical and, where applicable, ongoing services. It includes route names, the cities connected, the dates of operation commencement and cessation, and pertinent notes such as service replacements and renamings. The table facilitates understanding of the development of regional rail service, offering insights into service longevity, adjustments in routing, and the evolution of service names.

Header: Name, Route, Service began, Service ended, Notes
Entries:
Salt City Express: Service from New York City to Syracuse, operational from May 1974 to April 1981, succeeded by Electric City Express.
Saratogian, Sleepy Hollow, Spa Express, Spuyten Duyvil: Routes between New York City and Saratoga Springs or Albany, listed without specific operational dates.
Storm King: Two entries indicating service from New York City to Albany and Schenectady, starting April 1981, with no end date provided.
Washington Irving: Includes service to Albany and Schenectady from November 1974 to April 1981, with the Schenectady service replaced by Hudson Highlander.
Water Level Express: Detailed as operating between New York City and Buffalo/Niagara Falls from May 1974, with the Buffalo service ending in January 1978 and subsequent renaming.

Amtrak Routes■■■■Amtrak operates inter-city rail service in 46 of the 48 contiguous U.S. states and three Canadian provinces. Amtrak is a portmanteau of the words America and trak, the latter itself a sensational spelling of track. Amtrak service is divided into three categories of routes: Northeast Corridor routes, state-supported routes, and long distance routes. These types indicate how the service is funded. Northeast Corridor service is directly subsidized by federal appropriations. Federally-supported long distance services are subsidized by appropriations under a separate line item from the NEC in federal budgets. Additionally, Amtrak partners with 17 states to provide additional short- and medium-distance services desired by those states. They are subsidized by periodic payments to Amtrak from the state partners. Three routes – the Carolinian, Northeast Regional, and Vermonter – are state-subsidized only on the sections of their routes off the Northeast Corridor (north of New Haven, and south of Washington).■■■■The Northeast Regional and San Joaquin have branches served by different trips, while the Empire Builder and Lake Shore Limited split into two sections to serve branches. On the Capitol Corridor, Cascades, Empire Service, Keystone Service, Northeast Regional, and Pacific Surfliner, some or all trips do not run the full length of the route.■■■■Empire Corridor■■■■The Empire Corridor is a 461-mile (742 km) passenger rail corridor in New York State running between Penn Station in New York City and Niagara Falls, New York. Major cities on the route include Poughkeepsie, Albany, Schenectady, Amsterdam, Utica, Syracuse, Rochester, and Buffalo. Much of the corridor was once part of the New York Central Railroad's main line.■■■■Trains operating over the Empire Corridor (the former New York Central Railroad Water Level Route) are now collectively known as the Empire Service. The name was used by the New York Central beginning in 1967, but dropped by Amtrak in 1971. Amtrak restored the Empire Service brand with the June 11, 1972, timetable, and added individual train names on the May 19, 1974, timetable.

Amtrak restored the Empire Service brand with the June 11, 1972, timetable, and added individual train names on the May 19, 1974, timetable. As was done on the Northeast Corridor with NortheastDirect, individual train names for New York-Albany and New York-Niagara Falls service were dropped on October 28, 1995, and replaced with Empire. The individual names were re-added in November 1996, but dropped in favor of Empire Service in May 1999.
